<emphasis id="B19A7F7DFFBFFFC2FF49FD28B536FD5F" box="[166,297,702,723]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="211">Meta minima</emphasis>
: 
<bibRefCitation id="E77FDE9EFFBFFFC2FEDBFD2BB5D8FD5F" author="Denis, J." box="[308,455,701,723]" pageId="6" pageNumber="211" pagination="1 - 118" refId="ref4624" refString="Denis, J. 1962. Les araignees de l'archipel de Madere (Mission du Professeur Vandel). Publicacoes do Instituto Zoologia Doutor Augusto Nobre, 79, 1 - 118." type="journal article" year="1962">Denis, 1962: 82</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</treatmentCitation>
(elevated from subspecies); 
<treatmentCitation id="024F857EFFBFFFC2FD39FD2BB7ADFD5F" author="Wunderlich, J." box="[726,946,701,723]" page="363" pageId="6" pageNumber="211" year="1992">
<bibRefCitation id="E77FDE9EFFBFFFC2FD39FD2BB7ADFD5F" author="Wunderlich, J." box="[726,946,701,723]" pageId="6" pageNumber="211" pagination="1 - 619" refId="ref5218" refString="Wunderlich, J. 1992. Die Spinnen-Fauna der Makaronesischen Inseln: Taxonomie, Okologie, Biogeographie und Evolution. Beitrage zur Araneologie, 1, 1 - 619." type="journal article" year="1992">Wunderlich, 1992: 363</bibRefCitation>
</treatmentCitation>
, f. 330–332 (♂, 
<specimenCount id="95E868E6FFBFFFC2FBA2FD2AB043FD5F" box="[1101,1116,700,723]" pageId="6" pageNumber="211" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
).
</treatmentCitationGroup>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8351A36FFFBFFFC2FF34FD62B07AFCE3" blockId="6.[166,1225,756,879]" pageId="6" pageNumber="211">
Note. The species was described from the Canary Islands. 
<bibRefCitation id="E77FDE9EFFBFFFC2FC64FD62B072FC83" author="Wunderlich, J." box="[907,1133,756,783]" pageId="6" pageNumber="211" pagination="44 - 139" refId="ref5248" refString="Wunderlich, J. 2008. Descriptions of fossil spider (Araneae) taxa mainly in Baltic amber, as well as on certain related extant taxa. Beitrage zur Araneologie, 5, 44 - 139." type="journal article" year="2008">Wunderlich (2008)</bibRefCitation>
already doubted that its belonging to 
<taxonomicName id="44EED8ECFFBFFFC2FDEAFC83B65DFCA2" baseAuthorityName="WSC" baseAuthorityYear="2017" box="[517,578,789,814]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Meta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="211" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B19A7F7DFFBFFFC2FDEAFC83B65DFCA2" box="[517,578,789,814]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="211">Meta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and presumed that it could be a member of 
<taxonomicName id="44EED8ECFFBFFFC2FBBCFC82B0DDFCA2" authorityName="Chamberlin &amp; Ivie" authorityYear="1941" box="[1107,1218,788,814]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Metellina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="211" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B19A7F7DFFBFFFC2FBBCFC82B0DDFCA2" box="[1107,1218,788,814]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="211">Metellina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The shape of the male palp and epigyne, as well as the size (smaller than 
<taxonomicName id="44EED8ECFFBFFFC2FBC0FCA3B073FCC2" baseAuthorityName="WSC" baseAuthorityYear="2017" box="[1071,1132,821,846]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Meta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="211" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">
<emphasis id="B19A7F7DFFBFFFC2FBC0FCA3B073FCC2" box="[1071,1132,821,846]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="211">Meta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="AAA9C206FFBFFFC2FB99FCA2B0A5FCC3" box="[1142,1210,820,847]" pageId="6" pageNumber="211" sensu="stricto">s. str.</taxonomicNameLabel>
), indicate that it belongs to 
<taxonomicName id="44EED8ECFFBFFFC2FE38FCC2B659FCE2" authorityName="Chamberlin &amp; Ivie" authorityYear="1941" box="[471,582,852,878]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Metellina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="211" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B19A7F7DFFBFFFC2FE38FCC2B659FCE2" box="[471,582,852,878]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="211">Metellina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and therefore we suggest a new combination.
</paragraph>
